Yes.

The Constitution is intentionally sparse.

It's not meant to be a progenitor for all laws, thought it
has primacy over all laws.

It franked most of pre-existing law, while making only a few
laws &quot;unconstitutional&quot; by its sudden fiat.

What it did is create a federal government that was
previously handled in Blighty.

Many states have written laws that predate the Constitution.

And just about every state will have case law that reaches
back to English common law as the basis for some decisions.

