There is no &quot;right of ownership&quot;.  If you own something
you have a right to protect it in certain ways.

All land ownership is limited.  Metaphysically by your
ability to prevent trespass and the term of your life,
but legally by the fact that all land in the US originally
belonged to the government and was deeded with covenants
and falls under the principle of eminent domain.

You own the things you own, but you only own a portion of
the rights to your land.

Does that answer your question, or does it just prove
what I predicted about the depth of your knowledge?

--Blair
